    2: {
      level: 2,
      summary: 'Urushiol-induced allergic contact dermatitis affects 50-70% of the population. The oil persists on surfaces and under fingernails. The rash is a type IV delayed hypersensitivity reaction. Treatment includes decontamination, topical steroids, and oral steroids for severe cases.',
      explanation: `## Understanding Urushiol Dermatitis

### The Plants
- Poison ivy (Eastern US)
- Poison oak (Western US)
- Poison sumac (swampy areas)
- All contain urushiol oil

### The Allergen
- Urushiol is a resin
- Remains active on surfaces for years
- Can spread from tools, pets, clothes
- Smoke from burning plants can cause airway irritation

### The Reaction
- Type IV hypersensitivity (delayed)
- Sensitization required (first exposure may not cause rash)
- 12-72 hour onset
- Linear streaks of vesicles typical
- Not contagious (rash doesn't spread urushiol)

## Treatment

### Mild Cases
- Wash with soap and water (within 10-15 min ideal)
- Cool compresses
- Calamine lotion
- Topical hydrocortisone
- Oral antihistamines for itch

### Severe Cases
- Extensive rash (>20% body)
- Face or genital involvement
- Oral prednisone taper (2-3 weeks)
- Short tapers result in rebound

## Prevention
- Barrier creams (bentoquatam)
- Long clothing
- Immediate washing after exposure`,
      keyTerms: [
