      level: 3,
      summary: 'Urushiol-induced contact dermatitis is a T-cell-mediated delayed hypersensitivity reaction. Clinical presentation varies with exposure amount and individual sensitivity. Management includes decontamination and appropriate duration corticosteroids for moderate-severe cases.',
      explanation: `## Pathophysiology

### Urushiol Chemistry
- Catechol derivatives
- Oxidizes on skin contact
- Becomes hapten when bound to proteins
- Langerhans cells process antigen

### Immune Response
- Initial exposure: sensitization
- Subsequent exposure: effector phase
- T-helper cells recognize antigen
- Cytokine release
- Inflammatory infiltrate

### Clinical Timeline
- Exposure to rash: 12-72 hours
- Peak severity: 1-14 days
- Resolution: 2-3 weeks (untreated)

## Clinical Features
- Intensely pruritic
- Erythema, papules, vesicles, bullae
- Linear streaks (plant brushing)
- Black spot sign (oxidized urushiol)
- No spread from blister fluid

## Management

### Decontamination
- Wash within 10-15 minutes ideal
- Soap and water effective
- Commercial products (Tecnu, Zanfel)
- Wash under fingernails

### Topical Therapy
- Calamine, oatmeal baths
- Topical corticosteroids (mid to high potency)
- Avoid on face, intertriginous areas

### Systemic Therapy
- Indications: extensive, face/genitals, severe symptoms
- Prednisone: start 1mg/kg/day
- Taper over 2-3 weeks
- Short tapers (5-7 days) cause rebound`,
