      explanation: `## Detailed Immunopathogenesis

### Sensitization Phase
1. Urushiol penetrates stratum corneum
2. Oxidation to quinone form
3. Covalent binding to skin proteins
4. Langerhans cell uptake
5. Migration to lymph nodes
6. T-cell sensitization (days)

### Elicitation Phase
1. Re-exposure to urushiol
2. Antigen presentation in skin
3. Memory T-cell activation
4. Cytokine release (IFN-γ, TNF-α, IL-17)
5. Inflammatory cascade
6. Keratinocyte damage
7. Clinical dermatitis (12-72 hrs)

## Clinical Variation

### Factors Affecting Severity
- Amount of urushiol
- Duration of contact
- Prior sensitization degree
- Body location (thin skin more reactive)
- Individual sensitivity

### Atypical Presentations
- Erythema multiforme-like
- Black spot sign
- Id reaction (autoeczematization)

## Evidence-Based Treatment

### Decontamination Studies
| Timing | Efficacy |
|--------|----------|
| <15 min | Very effective |
| 1-4 hours | Partially effective |
| >4 hours | Limited benefit |

### Systemic Corticosteroid Regimen
- Starting dose: 40-60mg prednisone
- Taper: reduce by 5-10mg every 2-3 days
- Total duration: 14-21 days
- Short courses (<7 days): 25% rebound rate

### Adjunctive Therapies
- Antihistamines: minimal itch benefit
- Topical steroids: adjunct for localized disease
- Wet dressings: acute weeping phase`,
